commentBody:
@SP

But let’s not harp on it?!?!?

(Or so we’ve been told)

@SP

“Its capital is Sanaa”

To be fair, there were a few stretchy/ambiguous entries in the grid…but that one made me think of the Celebrity Jeopardy sketches from 90s SNL

@SP

Amen. 

Let me feed the emus, for old time's sake.

@Chris

Congrats on the half! Hopefully no nagging injuries / soreness.  And now you have some free time! No more bricks!   Not sure if it’s on your bucket list. But if it is, the 140.6 is a whole other beast. 

Tri’s are pretty common mid life crisis activities. My friends and I went through it.  I am sure quite a few regulars here have, as well.

@Weak

Thanks to you, MIN finally clicked for me. Aha, the hand on a clock, not a human! 

When I read the clue, "what a big hand indicates," my mind went to the gutter and I giggled like a schoolgirl hearing about it for the first time, but of course none of the possible answers along those lines would fit in three squares.

@sotto voce

Wow. That’s as close as you can get to NSFW In these comments. And “little schoolgirls” should definitely not know that expression. 

Weak “big hands” Sauce.

@Francis

Did you take the clue for 8D to be a verb?  If you did,
One letter may be wrong.

@SP

You've just triggered a memory of a notebook i had when I was younger for the sole purpose of quotes I would jot down, from books, movies, poems, songs, etc.

The one I had from Aristophanes was "You can't teach a crab to walk straight."

@Wayne Harrison

Exactly as Francis said.

Looking anywhere in the universe other than at the grid and clues (yes, even at the keyboard for keyboard-based clues (stone tablet solvers don't have access to a keyboard, after all)) is a blue star for this OCD solver.

@Andrzej

The only correct answer.

My rule for myself is no looking up anything for new puzzles, and minimal looking up is permitted for archived ones, or as I like to call them, training puzzles.

@Cliff

I look up my naticks. When a name I don't know, especially an unusually spelled one, crosses another such name, or maybe an American abbreviation (of which there are too many to count), and I've exhausted all means of arriving at the concrete letter, I see nothing suspect about Googling the solution.

In archived puzzles I just reveal such squares.

@Wayne Harrison
Your puzzle your rules.
Sometimes I have to look up something in the older archive puzzles; if that happens I at least try to go old school like looking at a map rather than just googling the answer.

@dutchiris

That never occurred to me.  

That is a truly terrifying thought!

@Francis,

Or kind of sweet. 

They care enough about you to yank your chain a little bit!

@sonnel

I've never been called out so poetically, hah!
But here's the thing – Argentinians also don’t root for Brazil, so all is fair in love and soccer! It's fervor at its best, not jealousy. ;-)

@sotto voce. I always remember that no less than Richard Feynman, noted genius, spent an ocean voyage to Rio de Janeiro studying Spanish so he could converse when he got there.

The typical US understanding of Brazil and Argentina is somehow thus illustrated.

It was your LEGS, EYE, BUTTS.... triggered my memory of the kiss applied by Absolon to the "nether ye"... note the Middle English spelling of eye... that is the hear too the MIller's Tale by Chaucer.

@Patrick J.
I was just reading something that repeatedly used 'anointed' in that original sense of daubing with oil. Like, even lubricating machinery was 'anointing' it.
Now when I apply valve oil to my cornet it pleases me to think of it as anointment.

@NanuNanu
Those are cheap, worthless dictionaries not worthy of the name, the cost, or the usage.  
Even m-w takes shortcuts to keep its size small.

@Caz
I was taught big hand for the minute hand. I don't remember hour hands being much, if any, wider. I'm looking at an analog clock right now that has the hour and minute hands the same width, as do almost all of the watches on the Timex site--the brand we always had.

Now I'm wondering whether it depended on the brand of clock hanging in your first grade school room!

@Alex,
Mandela effect!  I was reading your comment aloud, and my daughter said “sounds like it could be the Mandela effect”, just before I got to the point where you wrote “…feels like a Mandela effect, and now I’m questioning my sanity.”

We shared a nice chuckle on that!

@Andrzej 

Many top-tier athletes end up with medical issues that stay with them the rest of their lives. If you're competing with the world's best, you're likely to be pushing your body to the point of permanent damage. That's acceptable to a lot of people, but it doesn't seem worth it to me.

I was pretty happy to have been able to tun a six-minute mile when I was younger, and now that I'm in my seventies my knees are fine. That probably wouldn't have been true if I'd been trying to break records in my twenties.

@CCNY

I like my sport of choice (climbing) because it's fun, and the cool side effect is that it keeps me reasonably fit. Win-win.

I can't stand any sort of exercise routine. Put me in a gym and I'll cry. It's just so boring.

@Bruce

That's why the best athletes have the best physios. In fact, my physio was an athlete herself (an international medalist in rowing), and she went the career path for herself because she knew how sorely athletes needed good physios.

In fact, I started seeing her because even though I'm very much an amateur, I started to experience my sport's toll on my body. With physiotherapy all those issues went away and in my mid-40s I'm more limber than ever (in adulthood, anyway).

@Ms. Billie M. Spaight

The crossword and Connections are the only two NYT puzzles I do, and I love both.

In Connections, I find it easier to write down the groups as I find them.  I don't enter any until I've figured out all four.  In some case I can't see the final one, so I just make sure I feel  confident about three.  That keeps you from being caught in the red herring trap and eliminates the frustration.

@Anita 

Clues that are not precisely correct but are close enough to allow a solver to reason out the answer are a subtle form of misdirection.

People who like crosswords also tend to have large vocabularies that allow them to say things succinctly, but if you insist on precision in your crossword clues you should also get used to easier puzzles.

@Helen Wright
For alcohol: see 'on the SAUCE', 'hitting the SAUCE', and the sublimely simple 'SAUCED'.

And the Argentina vs. England argument about the Falklands is like my favourite definition of democracy: two wolves and a lamb voting about what to have for lunch.

@Jane Wheelaghan

Perhaps it's an art lab!

There's a great Calvin and Hobbes with the quote: "don't knock my smock or I'll clean your clock!" I say it every time smocks are mentioned. My family is definitely not tired of it.

@Suzanne
chirashi bowl at 43A
Not for sure it's Japanese, but....

@Joe P
Well, if you ever get a "cognitive test" called a MOCA (Mochie) you'll be asked to draw a clock and then to have it show "Eleven-ten" or "Ten past Eleven."  And you'd better do a nice job that includes the numerals, and the two hands had better be the right sizes or you lose points.  (This is just a tip-off.)  
It's a very basic test (name the 3 animals, remember 5 words, repeat  my sentences) so it only catches fairly impaired individuals......  cough cough not mentioning any names, but if anyone brags about their high scores, it's pretty sad....

@Xword Junkie
Yes, sorta....if you bake bread fairly often.  

And as to the YAP business, it would be used by someone wanting negate or downplay a legitimate complaint or issue  ("Aw, quit yer YAPping"= "We don't want to hear your harangue") so as to  siphon off its effect or value.  Happens to women all the time, I might add.

@The X-Phile

That reminds me of José Díaz-Balart, who anchors the Saturday edition of NBC Nightly News. He introduces a reporter, Monica Alba, as Moe-Nee-Kah Ahl-vah, while the other six days, she’s just Mah-nih-kuh Al-buh. 

He pronounces “Priscilla Thompson” like the rest of us.

@Mean Old Lady

I agree with your post above, but how does that make mastering the cube different?  It’s an exercise in logic and spatial relationships. I am no good whatsoever with the latter, but those guys seemingly effortlessly solving the cube are either thinking as they go, or have become so good that they have internalized what to do. 

If you can’t do it at that level, you can appreciate that there’s a lot of learning involved.

@Steve L
I take my cue from the Wordle Bot:  if you win, it's just LUCK pure LUCK,!

Ha, you make a point.  If I could discern between Left and Right, I might agree, but those are  very trickly concepts, always shifting around.  (I almost always get Up and Down...)

@Nancy
Well, I see it this way:  the book is a longish one, told in first person, and including a lot of unspoken thoughts (which many of us suppress, thus depriving the reading public of, for instance, a truly fun bon mot, or a quotable quote....)  And where did we hear what Huck Finn called his dad?--another recent example.

  Some of Jane Eyre's experiences are accounts of the Bronté girls' lives in boarding school, as governesses, etc.  (Louisa May Alcott's character Jo, an American version...)  If Jane Eyre is so "dull" why do we keep reading her story?

@RozzieGrandma

QUETZALCOATL was an answer in just one puzzle - a Saturday from June 16, 2001. So it wasn't a theme answer.

....

@Amy
Agreed, it was a fun puzzle.
I needed all four indulgences in Connections today.

@Norwood

I don't know!

This brought to you by Captain Ignorance! See you next week!

@Asher B.
Hey!  What's with the put-down about hand-cranked Victrolas?? And for that matter, the Brunswick Ultona and the Edison Gramophone?  And my Regina Music Box???

Where would YOU be without "recorded sound"?  Eh?
